results.title: S - Wikipedia
results.content: Nineteenth letter of the Latin alphabet This article is about the nineteenth letter of the alphabet. **S**, or **s**, is the nineteenth letter "Letter (alphabet)") of the Latin alphabet, used in the English alphabet, the alphabets of other western European languages and other latin alphabets worldwide. Ancient Greek did not have a /ʃ/ "sh" phoneme, so the derived Greek letter Sigma "Sigma (letter)") (Σ) came to represent the voiceless alveolar sibilant /s/. The original name of the letter "Sigma" may have been *san*, but due to the early history of the Greek epichoric alphabets, "san" came to be identified as a separate letter, Ϻ "San (letter)"). In most languages that use the Latin alphabet, ⟨s⟩ represents the voiceless alveolar or voiceless dental sibilant /s/.
